<subSubSection id="90C86550AD3DB50BFF722CD0C9DAFEB3" lastPageId="84" lastPageNumber="85" pageId="83" pageNumber="84" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="D86D36DBAD3DB50BFF722CD0C9DAFEB3" blockId="83.[151,1436,2014,2041]" lastBlockId="84.[151,1437,151,537]" lastPageId="84" lastPageNumber="85" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">
<emphasis id="EAA6EAC9AD3DB50CFF722CD0CB03F82E" bold="true" box="[151,274,2014,2040]" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Differently from 
<taxonomicName id="1FD24D58AD3DB50CFE3B2CD1C878F82F" authorityName="Holmberg. Scale" authorityYear="1886" box="[478,617,2015,2041]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Augochlora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="83" pageNumber="84" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="iphigenia">
<emphasis id="EAA6EAC9AD3DB50CFE3B2CD1C878F82F" box="[478,617,2015,2041]" italics="true" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">A. iphigenia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, females lack the well-developed tooth anteriorly on hypostomal carina and males have a yellowish band on clypeus apex. From 
<taxonomicName id="1FD24D58AD3AB50BFCC72B99C988FF67" authority="Lepeco &amp; Gonçalves, 2020" authorityName="Lepeco &amp; Gonçalves" authorityYear="2020" box="[802,921,151,177]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Augochlora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mendax" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="EAA6EAC9AD3AB50BFCC72B99C988FF67" box="[802,921,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">A. mendax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="EAA6EAC9AD3AB50BFC442B99C9EDFF67" bold="true" box="[929,1020,151,177]" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="F19557B2AD3AB50BFC442B99C9EDFF67" box="[929,1020,151,177]" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
it differs in the lack of a tuberculate elevation on female S1 and on the long and parallel-sided hind basitarsus of the males. From 
<taxonomicName id="1FD24D58AD3AB50BFB252BB5CF23FF02" authorityName="Strand" authorityYear="1910" box="[1216,1330,187,213]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Augochlora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="morrae">
<emphasis id="EAA6EAC9AD3AB50BFB252BB5CF23FF02" box="[1216,1330,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">A. morrae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it can be separated by the punctate preepisternum, the anterior border of mesoscutum not rugulose and the glabrous patch medially on male S5, along with the microreticulate metapostnotum posterior surface in both sexes. On the females, the gena and postgena can be weakly striate, but never as strong as in 
<taxonomicName id="1FD24D58AD3AB50BFC7A2A29CE1EFE96" authorityName="Strand" authorityYear="1910" box="[927,1039,295,321]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Augochlora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="morrae">
<emphasis id="EAA6EAC9AD3AB50BFC7A2A29CE1EFE96" box="[927,1039,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">A. morrae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName id="1FD24D58AD3AB50BFBF82A29CEB5FE96" authorityName="Vachal" authorityYear="1911" box="[1053,1188,295,321]" class="Insecta" family="Halictidae" genus="Halictus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aurinasis">
<emphasis id="EAA6EAC9AD3AB50BFBF82A29CEB5FE96" box="[1053,1188,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">A. aurinasis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is also remarkable for the abundant golden reflections, which may turn into copper on the head.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
